#For this question, a linear mixed model was used. A mixed model was applied because fixed and random effects are both present (fixed=explanatory variables, random=correlation w/in tank). The groups have been randomly selected from a population of groups. Observations from within the same tanks are most likely correlated, but tadpoles between sites are not. There are two covariates, predation and resource level. The random effect factor is the individual tanks. Based on the qqplot the data distribution is skewed to the right. There are two random effects, the unique tanks and the leftover residual variance. The random effects help to explain how much variation there is in the relationship between the mass of the tadpoles and predators/resources due to the fact that observations were from different tanks. Linearity in the xyplot supports the use of Wald's confidence intervals and the results of the density plot show that the data is Gaussian. The data is very underdispersed (based on gof results). Best model type to use is Gaussian based on the density plot and there are no counts or survival data. The results of the anova (chisq) show that:

#1) Leftover residual error has a higher standard deviation (variance) than the individual tanks.

#2) Predation has a significant effect on the final mass of the tadpoles.

#3) Resource availability had no significant effect on the final mass of the tadpoles.

Question 2

The data set for this question is called plantData.

This study was conducted at multiple sites throughout Florida. At each location there were three plots that were randomly assigned to one of two growth enhancement treatments (Growth_A or Growth_B) or to a control treatment (Control). You can think of sites as a blocking variable. The number of surviving plants from the total number planted at an earlier time point is measured in each plot. However, note the the total number of plants planted (column num_samped) at each site differed a little. So each survival estimate is based on a different number of individuals.

Conduct an appropriate statisitcal analysis to determine if there were differences in the propotion of plants that survived in the two growth enhanced and control plots.

library(car)

plantData<-read.csv("~/GitHub/plant_Data.csv")

for(i in 1:length(plantData$y)){

  if(plantData$y[i] > plantData$num_samp[i]){

    plantData$y[i] = plantData$num_samp[i]}}

plantData$survivalRate <- (plantData$y/plantData$num_samp)

ggplot(plantData,aes(x = treatment, y = survivalRate, colour = site)) + geom_boxplot(size=2)

plantData$site <- factor(plantData$site)

plantData$treatment <- factor(plantData$treatment)

resp_vec=cbind(plantData$num_samp-plantData$y,plantData$y)

mod3<-glm(resp_vec~treatment,data=plantData,family="quasibinomial")

gof(mod3)
## D  = 101.665, df = 18, P(>D) = 1.096269e-13
## X2 = 92.1855, df = 18, P(>X2) = 5.837877e-12
anova(mod3, test="F")
pred.data = data.frame(plantData,predict(mod3, plantData, type = "link", se.fit=TRUE))

pred.data=within(pred.data, {

  predvals <- plogis(fit)

  LL <- plogis(fit - 1.96 * se.fit)

  UL <- plogis(fit + 1.96 * se.fit)})

ggplot(data=pred.data,aes(x=treatment,y=predvals))+

  xlab("Treatment")+

  ylab("Proportion of plants surviving")+geom_line()+

  geom_ribbon(aes(ymin=LL,ymax=UL),alpha=.2)+

  geom_point(data=plantData,aes(x = treatment, y = survivalRate))

#For this question, the response variable is discrete and is NOT count data, which means it is a type of binomial linear model. Since the data set consists of the proportion of plants that survive, Bernoulli(0/1) testing will not work. After running the gof diagnostic, it is seen that the data are way overdispersed, which leads to the use of a quasibinomial test, which specifies weights to indicate the denominator. Based upon the results of the anova test, the treatment levels do have a significant impact on the proportion of plants which survive. the data was modified originally to remove data points that had a higher y value than the original num-samp data (in order to run the diagnostic).

Question 3 In this experiment, 25 pregnant mouse dams were randomly selected. From each dam the researchers selected 3 pups. The pups were randomly assigned to a vehicle only control group ("cont_+veh) or to a vehicle plus microcystin (micro+veh") treatment group and a sulforaphane plus microcystin treatment group (micro+_sulf"). The experiment was designed to test whether the sulforaphane supplement could reduce liver toxicity caused by exposure to microcystins (a toxin that is generated from some forms of harmful algal blooms). Following exposures of all three pups from each dam to the algal toxins, liver biopsies were collected and examined via histology. The researchers counted the number of lesions observed becuase they are indicative of liver toxicity. Because they selected only one histology section from each individual there were many instances where they may have failed to observe lesions.

Analyse the mouse_liver data set to determine if those mice that received the sulforaphane supplements had lower levels of liver pathology due to the toxins. Provide a figure and an interpretation of the results.
